O933B6iTVhWF0DX4uPID5Apf_dEeMpB-fPVcg8jTUL9tXXCHZsXS4nuETE_ZGuBuLo-XaYAdftDSLZZj0MVsCtJQknLon2YsgeuIWep_UmCJPhmj1WFTGaw66i4o5o7kSdXgXLFjF5sHXCX_rk-eImv0bUF-teNhZl72zCQshxq0eSRB04B6voK0i7x0q1lp5QDVyi0DgoKjJQF_amQEV3_rixhCVB1v0c0CxakKgPkM45e7GV5U5BpwUBSyaG-RHje_xIKHsq8SsPaCLvL_LgPo85QlN_J7nWMU-UIBpkgiFF2yBXrEDaXxdePaSd0lgBkc9LknG09PucLktEQ-fiibiiN65ctYzcroO3pA_LPbyzEx-G62PZIjY-QAdeW5DNW4xcPsMVUrMB2UJFyD61QZ8MrAMSUDH2S_J9XNv-TkXXRpiBlk2Mxwv4gRkd2_2BKZPM0tLayG0UzhU1DU7JksZ4j7039ypzs0H6MeCxsfVM9wAuOn7MF47SIzzqHrhaMVELdjWV3jmo_1kiPRb96ZBOKBIWXhy4fsMCJ9UQauSXFj03TXkfkFWwrdSy_MlIDRM5MXitNwp1HFehlFfIDhqHcI5VOcpjE3a8DaC8V9sveIs9KxMHF0y8lVWt9uBjdZi1_37Qqwm1-ckeLDyuwIR2Pbfe5QSW8duxgoWkP53ieBK0SJRMI3tCfVv90ssEYodDmsBpAucYdSnVWoZhwUkH4RzqSM0CRU5ORpV_KIKm5Ny4KECTk-RYoTAN9djPgzja3K3YEMELYNEd0wa3VGjkJ6jELIb6VWADBPMKprpKgeTOrOrfmYo2xwHwmfV8DH1oRPbxc1hgVOtx0Sd4ZKG-Ae_dqWFZGGyyEbwEs8cSto0UkxABvat2HLn8IX_6jv1h3iiCr7NeYAB5_FNN50Agl312vPqetwkeO2qZzBW6AIsf7e9YevA_uHpdjfxXL5SPSI2-UuFzCsJ3xqxGKB2iExgcZYvsv0n1De_on1WuO4e8tAHvexmjrNQQ82u9VNmwSpY-6QU-0vKyAB4Du-Dn-rC52dhrXhf8_HaVHZEY1smoIsjOoDnZsb52bRQctgd9T_GUX9Xs3xegDoLELSJF2sE15a8q73BAdRaiq-w==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class resources in native images**\\n\\nI'm considering whether our test class bytes are included as resources. In native applications, class resources might not be included unless specified. However, existing metadata could include all test resources, which is interesting. The Native Image can access class resources, and using `ClassLoader.getResourceAsStream(\\\"org/foo/Bar.class\\\")` usually returns class bytes in the JVM. Still, I’m not sure if that applies to native unless included. For our tests, if the JVM reads the resource stream, the agent records resource metadata. I wonder about the implications for user code.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reassessing classpath for tests**\\n\\nI’m considering a better approach where instead of using the actual build/classes root, I create a temporary classpath root with copies of the relevant test class `.class` files. This ensures they’re loaded as resources. Then, the JUnit Launcher will scan this directory to discover class names. The classloader is required to load these classes by name because they’re already present in the image or JVM. By having the `.class` files in the temporary root, we make discovery easier. Do I need to copy the top-level files?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing class loading issues**\\n\\nI'm considering if the scanner needs to return a class from a different loader. It appears it's using the same classloader, but maybe the classpath root in the temp directory isn't on the context classloader. The `selectClasspathRoots` selectors are supposed to guide the engine to scan roots, yet by default, the ClassLoader may only access the original test classpath and not the temp root. Since the class is also on the original classpath, it's loaded as the same class.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ynb48TYabnn5qnhnYmt21B2b|fc_0a9e76e99fd0de06016a28c07dd1ac8190914f88abd157cb20", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/build.gradle", "edits": [{"oldText": "    testImplementation \"org.springframework:spring-context:$libraryVersion\"\n    testImplementation 'junit:junit:4.13.2'\n", "newText": "    testImplementation \"org.springframework:spring-context:$libraryVersion\"\n    testImplementation 'org.junit.jupiter:junit-jupiter:6.0.0'\n    testImplementation 'junit:junit:4.13.2'\n    testRuntimeOnly 'org.junit.platform:junit-platform-launcher:6.0.0'\n    testRuntimeOnly 'org.junit.vintage:junit-vintage-engine:6.0.0'\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 999, "output": 1797, "cacheRead": 38400, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 41196, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timesta